{
  "text": "DDR2 is the major tyrosine-phosphorylated protein in 3D collagen matrices. Based on the significance of phosphorylation on the tyrosine residues in a variety of signal proteins to transmit the intracellular signaling in response to specific environmental cues, we carried out the immunoprecipitation experiment with phospho-tyrosine antibodies using cell lysates that were prepared from 3D collagen matrices to identify the 3D environment-specific tyrosine-phosphorylated proteins and analyzed by MALDI-TOF mass spectrometry. Fig. 1A shows that several proteins increased the tyrosine phosphorylation in 3D collagen matrices. DDR2 (~134 kDa) was found to be the most prominent protein to increase the tyrosine phosphorylation in 3D collagen matrices. In particular, DDR2 enhanced the phosphorylation in response to PDGF stimulation. It has been reported that the DDRs only respond to extracellular components such as fibrillar collagens, but not to soluble growth factors [CITATION_1] . However, our findings indicate that DDR2 appeared likely to increase the phosphorylation upon PDGF stimulation in 3D collagen matrices. Thus, it may be beneficial to define whether DDR2 can respond to soluble growth factors, such as PDGF, when cells are in the 3D environment.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "46610692"
